		<tr>
			<td class="BoardRowB" colspan=3>
				I posted the about half of the info below on another board, but it might be useful for you in deciding what class and race to play on a pvp server. <br>  <br> I have to strongly agree with the gentleman who posted (on another board) that the best choice of shadowknights was Ogre SK with 5 points in agility and 15 points in intelligence.  <br>  <br> I am currently a level 30 Ogre SK, and since this is my first and basically my only character, I didn't choose quite that wisely when allocating my initial starting points, since I had never played before. If I knew then what I know now, you can bet I would have chosen 5 in agility and 15 in intelligence. <br>  <br> The reason for this is that for agility, if you go below 75 you start taking huge hits to your armor class. I found this out the hard way when Kagian the wood-elf druid pk'd me (ah the joys of meeting someone eight levels higher than you and hostile on Vallon Zek) and took my silver-plated leggings and I had to wear shin gauntlets instead.  (Oh yeah, 10 plat bounty for the death of Kagian. No limit -- bounty paid for EACH and EVERY time you kill him. *grin*) <br>  <br> The armor class for both is the same -- however there was a drastic difference in my armor class with the shin gauntlets rather than the silver-plated leggings. The reason? The bonus to agility from the silver-plated leggings. Apparently you suffer a significant penalty to your armor class if you have agility below 75.  <br>  <br> Since ogre SK's have a base agility of 70, it makes a lot of sense to put five points into agility to bring your agility up to 75 and eliminate the harsh AC penalties associated with being below 75. <br>  <br> The next choice is intelligence. At least ten points in here is mandatory. Fifteen is recommended. Why? Well the obvious reason is that intelligence determines your mana. But perhaps less obviously, intelligence determines the rate at which you learn a lot of important skills. <br>  <br> If you ever want to be a skilled fletcher (or smith or tailor or whatever) then you will want your skills to go up as quickly as possible -- and that means intelligence. Fletching is worth learning as an SK simply because using a good bow and decent arrows are mandatory to be a skilled shadowknight. <br>  <br> This also affects the rate at which you learn other important skills, like sense heading and swimming. When a naked Erudite wizzie attempts to blast you in the Oasis (yes, this means you, Zubik) and you shadowstep into water, it's nice to know which way you are facing and be able to swim -- this way you end up swimming to saftey rather than to the island with the spectres or worse, floundering dead in the water while being blasted from shore. <br>  <br> Let's look at the other options. You could put some points into strength. That would let you carry more loot and would help you hit for more damage. This is a good choice, but there are plenty of ways to raise your strength (especially at higher levels) and with any type of weight reduction pack you can easily carry more stuff. Items that boost strength are cheaper and easier to come by than items that boost intelligence (think Jagged Bands at 40 plat for 5 AC +3 Str compared to platinum rose engagement rings at 400 plat for +4 Int). <br>  <br> Stamina is a horrible choice to put any points. With starting stamina of 127, you have all the stamina you will ever need. You generally don't need to be able to swim or fight longer than 127 stamina, and the Darkforge armor you will (hopefully) eventually aquire gives a whopping +22 stamina more -- so if you want more stamina, you will be able to get it without too many problems just by doing the shadowknight armor quests. <br>  <br> Higher agility can be nice since you can run slightly faster (although it's barely noticeable) but the real reason is better AC. Better AC is huge, since you will get hit less frequently, and when you do get hit, it will be for less damage if you have better AC. All-in-all, AC will keep you alive in melee combat. <br>  <br> Higher dex can be nice when shooting a bow or trying to get a weapon to proc. But again, dex can be easily pumped with items -- darkmail gauntlets, lizardscale cloak, grotesque mask all give +5 or more dex. Since archery skill is maxed out at 75, your bow won't be quite as usefull as that of a ranger, warrior, or rogue. It's been my experience that with only 71 dex, weapons proc frequently enough (stiletto of the bloodclaw, dark reaver, and vampiric touch) and that arrows already do enough damage and hit frequently enough not to warrant further increases in dex. <br>  <br> Wisdom? Forget about it. Not worth even considering. Don't waste any points here, you gain negligible benefits compared to putting the points into intelligence. <br>  <br> Charisma? Forget about that, too... you will get a little bit better prices, but a crude stein for +15 cha and/or some +7 cha bracelets will give you decent enough prices if you are worried about buying or selling something from a vendor, provided you have been smart with your factions as well. <br>  <br> So to sum up for abilities -- 5 points into agility, 10 points into intelligence, and 5 points into your preference of intelligence, strength, agility, or dexterity -- my choice being intelligence, due to my enjoyment of the various trade skills. <br>  <br> So why an ogre? For one, you can freely travel all the dark cities -- Oggok, Neriak, and all of Grobb (except the lone tunnel with the troll shadowknight guild all the way at the back, but why would you want to go there anyway?), a perk that trolls do not enjoy (they tend to get killed by Chef Dooga rather than getting cool quests from her) and Iksar have negligible hope of obtaining.  <br>  <br> They have the best strength and stamina for the most damage and hit points, which make beat down and tanking fun. They have better intelligence than trolls which means more mana and quicker learning of skills. The poor starting agility can be compensated by allocating five points to the attribute, bringing the skill up to the acceptable level of 75.  <br>  <br> Infravision makes them superior to humans and erudites -- granted they will all get the spell to give infravision at level 22, but that can seem like a long wait. Slam makes them better than DE's for combat. Hide makes DE's appealing, but shadowknights will all get that at level 35 anyway. Beckon is Ogre and Troll only and would be a fearsome weapon (granted only Reipin has one on our server, but it's still fun to dream). <br>  <br> So why a shadowknight?  They don't solo as well as a necro or a druid and don't do as much DD as a wizard, after all... <br>  <br> There are a few reasons.  One is that shadow-knights are a tank.  That means that it will take a lot more damage to kill you than it would take to kill a caster, because you have higher hitpoints.  Just gettin' hit a few times is no reason to panic as a shadowknight -- get hit a few times as a caster, and it's time to run.  Higher AC than casters, plus higher HP, mean you won't crumple from a few hits from a MOB. <br>  <br> Another reason is the melee damage dealing ability.  You can swing a weapon for nice damage even if you are out of mana -- you won't be one of the casters whining that &quot;they only got me because I was out of mana&quot;, but rather a formidable foe even when your mana is low -- or gone.   <br>  <br> With harm-touch requiring no mana and almost impossible to interrupt (never happened to me yet), you have a sweet and sometimes unexpected finishing move.  You might get attacked by someone mistaking you for a warrior -- only for them to find out that two bubbles of health is too late for them to run away, as they writhe in the grip of agony. <br>  <br> However, unlike a warrior, you also have spells -- so you won't have quite as much trouble with casters as warriors do.  And not just any spells, but necro-based spells -- damage dealing nastiness!  (I keep telling my necro friends that they are lucky to get so many of the good shadowknight spells). <br>  <br> The spell selection of the shadowkngihts is actually pretty good, despite all the complaints about them on the board.  Yes, I too would like to see them get every necro spell at about ten levels after the necromancers get the spell.  However you get some things that are very good for PK.   <br>  <br> One is a short distance random teleport -- shadowstep.  This helps confuse your opponent and give you time to cast stuff or to escape when necessary.  Shadowstep has saved me on numerous occasions... pk attacks me when I'm at one bubble of health and one bubble of mana (they seem to like that) and I use last bubble of mana to shadowstep.  I wind up behind a hill or under water or somewhere that the pk can't see me and then either zone or bandage up to half and med, depending on the situation. <br>  <br> Also nice is the engulfing darkness -- good for either beating down the opponent trying to run away (sorry about your recent loss Jumm) or to slow down the pk enough that you can escape when you are in a hurry to meet someone in Kunark and don't have time to stop to kill the red-con rogue that was attacking you in EC (Go away! I'm on my lunch hour!) <br>  <br> Another thing that is nice about shadowknights is that they have a little bit of everything in them.  Jack of all trades, master of one -- beat-down.  You get to fire a bow like a ranger, drain life and dot like a necro, train a pet like a mage, cast direct damage like a wizard, ensnare like a druid, buff like a shaman, double attack like a warrior, hide and sneak around like a rogue, feign-pull and disarm like a monk, and debuff like an enchanter -- and all while damaging your adversary.   <br>  <br> However, shadowknigts have some skills that make them valuable in a group -- even if not everyone realizes it.   <br>  <br> In my opinion, shadowknights are hands-down the best puller in the game since they can pull with bow or with a selection of damaging or slowing spells and can feign death like a monk. <br>  <br> Also, in my opinion, shadowknights are the best taunters in the game -- something that can be fun to role-play as well... (Look at me when I'm hitting you! *grin*)  They can taunt, slash with sword for massive damage, slam, bash, cast, have pet taunt, or the ultimate taunt -- harm touch.  One way or another, that mob is going to leave the caster or rogue alone.  No other class has that many ways to taunt a mob off someone... a good shadowknight will quickly find friends in rogues and wizards. <br>  <br> I like it that I get to try out a little bit of a lot of different classes rather than just be tied down to doing one thing exclusively.  You might like that too... then if you find one aspect of being a shadowknight that you like better than any other, you will know what character to make as a second character.  One of my friends watching me play decided that he liked the massive in-your-face beatdown, so he made a warrior as his character.  Another decided that he liked the pet plus dot approach, so he made a necro. <br>  <br> Another class I would consider is enchanter, since most people don't seem to really know what their spells do.  Consequently, they don't know what to do to stop them.  Some other reasons to consider enchanters -- they are in high demand for groups, they get really strong trade skills, they get good crowd control, and they can often get the jump on their opponent through their clever use of illusion, and a lot of their spells can really mess people up bad -- mesmerize, for instance. <br>  <br> In each case, I like the variety of weapons in the arsenal.  The two classes I mentioned are difficult to play well -- poor players will whine a lot about the class being under-powered when in fact the class is balanced and only their skills are deficient -- but both shadowknights and enchanters are extremely powerful if played with skill and finesse.  In contrast, it is really hard to not be at least halfway decent as a DROOID DUDE, even for the lamest pre-teen newbie powergamer.   <br>  <br> I think only rogue (and maybe the enchanter) takes more skill than the shadowknight to play well -- and I've seen some VERY skilled rogues on Vallon Zek...   <br>  <br> All the posts whining that rogues are under-powered attests to the skill it takes to play the rogue class.  Granted, some of the posts are legitimate issues with broken rogue skills that need to be repaired... but in terms of class balance, especially as it pertains to pvp, most people don't have the necessary skill it takes to play a rogue I think.   <br>  <br> I believe that if you take a skilled rogue and an average player of another class, the rogue will end up walking away with an item that used to belong to the other player nine times out of ten.  But my opinions on rogue balance are best left to another post. <br>  <br> For both of these choices, shadowknight and enchanter, they are like the quarterback in a football team -- you need to master a wide variety of things to be good.  Not just block and tackle like a linesman, not just run like a halfback, not just catch like a reciever -- but plan, improvise, adapt, lead, run, throw, kick, lateral, handoff...   You need to develop a sense of timing -- when to do what.  Shadowknights need to be able to pull, tank, taunt, cast, kite, slash, bash, stab, buff, debuff, craft... the list goes on and on.  Shadowknights take a long time to level and a lot of patience to play right.  But the reward is a deadly damage-dealing juggernaught of a killing machine that starts to really shine at level 30. <br>  <br> Another thing that is fun is wandering around without anon turned on.  Most people will leave their characters in the &quot;anon&quot; mode.  But you don't have to do so.  Why?  People fear the harm touch.  The few people between levels 10 and 45  that I see that are confident enough in their abilities to go without &quot;anon&quot; on Vallon Zek are wizards (Xanathin and Pacaleka), enchanters (Daudi and occasionally others), monks (Ausculta), and shadowknights (me!).   <br>  <br> Below level ten nobody cares if you're not anon since you have no loot (except twinks, but that's another subject) and above 45 everyone knows who you are by then and you probably want to start thinking about the planes anyway since you've already made a name for yourself so that people know your class and rough level without looking.   <br> When picking a class to play, you might want to play one that is good enough that you don't care if other people know what class and level you are -- I haven't seen any non-anon druids, necros, shamans, mages, warriors, paladins, bards, or rogues -- if druids and necros are really that good, take off anon.  Then again, maybe it's the player and not the class that makes the difference.  Who can say. <br>  <br> With shadowknight, if you are bad at some aspects of the class, you will suffer a lot, but if you have mastered all the tools, you will be almost unstoppable (IMHO).  This is not a good choice for people who are poor at strategy and want a simplistic approach to the game.  You will fail and you will die.  But if you take the time to practice, learn, and master all the skills, you'll do quite well.  Once I finally got the hang of shadowstep at level 18, I have only been pk'd five times in twelve levels.  That's only once every two or three levels, which I suspect is below average for the server, based on the sheer number of times I got pk'd in pre-shadowstep days (I can only imagine what the warriors must go through... hang in there, Vizzini!). <br>        <br> Once to a necro eight levels higher, once to a druid eight levels higher, once while naked on a corpse run where I was in too much of a hurry to memorize spells (there's that &quot;skill&quot; factor coming in to play again... not too bright that time), once to a wizard five levels higher while at one bubble of health, one bubble of mana, and afk, and once due to getting ambushed in a dungeon in Kunark due to a party member trash-talking a group of reds one too many times and getting all of us ambushed -- I died stupidly even though I was at almost full health and almost full mana -- the element of surprise is a lethal weapon, folks. <br>  <br> That means that generally you don't get killed by people at or below your level, even when you find yourself in a bad situation.  I've had some cases where I survived against overwhelming odds -- one mage sent three earth pets in a row against me when I was marooned on an island in the ocean of tears -- starting the battle very low on both health and mana (around one bubble of each) from battling Nerbilik.  Another time low on health (three bubbles) and ambushed by a war party in the tunnels under Freeport, following their previous attack on the dock while waiting for the boat -- escaped to north ro followed by a lone bard -- he made the mistake of attaking me when I was at two bubbles of health (stupid green-con newbies) -- he should have brought the rest of his buddies, since I left his corpse to rot at the entrance of the tunnel to EC. <br>  <br> I'm still not at the level that I need to be, pvp skill-wise... but I'm practicing with pumice, re-arming after a disarm, shadowstep, ambush strategies, potions, and various triggered items (does hand of shadow work well for shadowknights? hmmm...) and slowly improving my stragies, tactics, and reflexes.  Pretty soon I'll be practicing on the lightie twinks that stumble into the darker places in Norrath, never to return to sunlit lands. <br>  <br> So I'm not yet the feared pk god that some of the players on the server are (congrats on gankin' the Ykesha... you know who you are...).  But I'll get there.  I'm practicing pvp and dueling (die Vlail) and sooner or later I'll write up some sort of pvp &amp; duel strategy guide.  But I'll wait until my skills are a little better at it first. <br>  <br> You can all say what you like about Bodda -- yeah he talks too much trash, yeah he's annoying, yeah he's an arrogant erudite wizard who should be put back in the grave -- but whenever I see a message about him being involved in a duel, he's on the winning side.  I wonder what strategies he's using to dominate dueling?  I gotta think that there are some strategies he's using that most could master if they knew and practiced them.  Maybe we should start a board about that sometime... instead of just boards of flames and counter-flames. <br>  <br> Well, it's obvious by now that this post is just plain long-winded.  Sorry for all the rambling, but I'm working on-call this week and only got one call today -- so what else to do but post to the boards? <br>  <br> Bolas Bonesmith <br> Olath Xukuth, Officer <br> 30th Rank Greenblood Ogre Shadowknight <br>  <br> Master Fletcher  <br> Master Smith  <br> Master Brewer <br> Master Potter <br> Master Baker <br> Journeyman Tailor <br> Apprentice Jeweler		

